results.notes:
Growing on the ground.
Estimating spore measurements is tricky, as the spores are coarsely ornamented, including the occasionally large projections at each end. Ornamentation forms a reticulatum. A few of the spores were observed to be bigutulate. Including the projections and spines I estimated the spore dimensions at 15-19 × 7-10 microns. Reported spore dimensions for A. aurantia vary from source to source. Mushroom Expert 18-24 × 9-11; C du Q 13-16(24) x 7.5-12; Lincoff 18-22 × 9-10; AF of NA 17-24 × 9-11; Arora 18-24 × 9-11. Mushroom Expert also mentions a variety found in western NA that has spore dimensions 12-15 × 5-6.5.
These fruit bodies appear to be a bit large for Melastiza chateri, and the margins lack brown hairs that would be expected with this species. However, I think it’s worth pointing out that (aside from macroscopic similarities) the spore morphologies of A. aurantia and M. chateri. Actually, as of my writing this, I have not completely convinced myself against the potential application of M. chateri to the Ascos seen in this observation.
